			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Looks like funding is the biggest question, and I admit it's a big one.  What about involving the international community?  The world of science seems to be one of the most peaceful in the world...which is to say on bigger projects that you often find people from several different nations and backgrounds working as a team.  Looks like we could learn a lot (and not just science) from the scientific community.
<br />

<br />
Another possible funding option would be to let corporations control some of the funding and planning.  I know that some people immidiatly go defensive when evil mega-corps are mentioned, but lets face it, they have the money and the oppritunity to gain ten-fold.  As someone pointed out, the asteroid belt is a perfect example.  I mean, it's basically raw meterail which has already been extracted.  Using gravitational movement, it wouldn't be hard to do a "pitch and catch" with an asteroid, slinging it around Mars and letting it be captured by Earth gravity (as long as you can find a sure-fire way to avoid the problem of slinging an asteroid INTO earth...which would be bad).
<br />

<br />
The moon would be another example of a good mining candidate.  We know that it was probably part of earth at one point and was sheered off in a gigantic collision with something during the primordial phase of planetary development...so it's safe to reason that we'd find the same base ores we do here on the moon, minus the fossile fuels.
<br />

<br />
The Universe Today web site (http://www.universetoday.com/) has some great information and a daily newsletter (usually with three to six stories) which I really like.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
