			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Robots can not make intuitive and snap decisions like a human being.  For instance in terms of military aircraft, I highly doubt that UAVs will replace human pilots any time soon.  There is just something about having an experienced person in the situation.  
<br />
You also must keep in mind that astronauts all have at least a PhD (or two) and post-doc experience.  They are not just some well trained monkeys flying a spacecraft.  Their education and expertise is what makes them valuable.
<br />

<br />
I think it would be great of corporations played more of a key in the space program.  Well as in running programs, private industry already runs the infrastructrure and production of the space program.  One massive problem, though, is that corporations are essentially only into whatever it is they do for one thing:  money.  I do not think that a private corporation would be able to make a profit, and therefore able to keep the shareholders happy.
<br />

<br />
In reference to the international community, that sounds all sorts of nice and everything but I do not think it is in our best interest as a country.  The US without a doubt has the most experience in space programs so there is not much other countries could offer to begin with.  I was reading an article in Newsweek that mentioned this recent Mars voyage and other countries have attempted to send probes there, and if I remember correctly they all have failed (even techno-wiz Japan botched big time).  The US itself has sent half a dozen probes there since the Viking circa 1970s.  I am aware of only one failure and that was the launch previous to this launch.
<br />

<br />
Sure, ideally, the space program should be a international effort, however I think the reality and practically of our national interest is that it should be primarily be a US ventrure with minor contracts to other countries.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
