	<tr>
		<td width="150" align="left" valign="top" class="row1"><span class="name"><a name="46186"></a><b>EvilNight</b></span><br /><span class="postdetails">Agent of the System<br />
		<br /><img class="avatar" src="http://www.eqluclin.com/forum/images/avatars/bunbun.gif" alt="" /><br />
		<br />Joined: 19 Jul 2003<br />Posts: 1180</span></td>
		<td class="row1" width="100%" height="28" valign="top">

		<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
			<tr>
			<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=46186&amp;sid=68a48ddcd6046b6856e76422b8a3c29f#46186"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Tue Jan 20, 2004 5:13 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: Re: Space Exploration; your thoughts</span></td>
				<td width="30%" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap" align="right"> <a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=46186&amp;sid=68a48ddcd6046b6856e76422b8a3c29f"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>   </td></tr></table></td>
			</tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				It's possible to terraform any planet. It's just a question of what levels of tech are needed and how many years (or hundreds of years) it'll take to convert the atmosphere. We're a damn long way off from any kind of Terraforming tech. Hell, we're just beginning to crack Nanotech, and that's going to be a required element (maybe the primary element) for Terraforming. If we tried it now we'd be like cavemen trying to build a supercomputer. You'd need to do everything from adjusting planetary rotations and orbits to converting atmospheric and ground elements to jump starting a working ecosystem. That's some heavy tech, and it touches on all disciplines of science. The cool thing about it is that every planet will be an entirely different engineering challenge.
<br />

<br />
Research into space technology is valuable because it advances many areas of science, engineering, and computing just in the process of designing the spaceships and tackling the collossal engineering problems inherent in space travel and survival in non-earth environments. Add to that the huge amount of knowledge gained when we actually get anywhere and it's definitely worth the risk. The problem most people have seeing this is that the knowledge gains are usually invisible, and take years to flow into the economy and into accepted science. It looks like science for the sake of science without a lot of immediate tangible results to justify the cost to the layman. In the end, though, it's easily one of the most worthwile scientific endeavours we are capable of.
<br />

<br />
Frankly I agree the only reason we are doing this is because of the "bigger %$#@! foreign policy theory", but if that's what it takes to get it done, fine with me. It's never a good time to do it. Do it anyway. Do it now.
<br />

<br />
If they want to slash the cost of this thing to nothing, then we need to send some men to mars and <span style="font-style: italic">leave</span> them there. Mars has about a third Earth's gravity, so a lift off from there is a hard trick to pull. The return trip is what's making this cost-prohibitive. If we send up a team with a lot (several years) worth of supplies, as well as equipment for building a shelter in that environment, they'll be able to live for years up there barring an accident. We can send them supply drops every two or so years when Earth is closest to Mars. Radiation levels are low enough for them to survive. The low gravity will eventually lead to health problems and the men up there will eventually die, but not before they bring us back more knowledge in a week than any number of unmanned probes can deliver within a hundred years. They could assemble a Mars-base that any future astronauts could use.
<br />

<br />
Don't kid yourself and think for a minute there would be a shortage of scientists willing to volunteer for a "suicide" mission like this, either. There are plenty of scientists out there willing to take one for the team now just like in the days of the early explorers.
<br />

<br />
Granted, there's a certain satisfaction in sending up a ship to Mars and then bringing them back home, but that's on the edge of our technology right now. As long as we are using solid fuel rockets, it's going to be a hard job. They'll probably design a space ship based on that caveman tech instead of working on ion drives, which is what our next rocket type will eventually be (since they've got working <a href="http://antwrp.gsfc.nasa.gov/apod/ap030720.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">prototypes</a> now.)
<br />

<br />
Our best bet for a return-capable craft would be to build a shuttle that has reusable (at least *once*) solid fuel boosters for lifting off of earth and ion drives for the travel out to Mars and from Mars back to Earth. You'd launch the thing from earth, then dock it with the ISS to refuel it with solid state fuel (or send up another shuttle to refuel it in orbit, either way works). Once refueled, it uses the ion drives to get to Mars. It'll need some fancy landing device (and I doubt the airbag solution they used for the rover is going to work on something this massive) to land on mars because it'll have a hard time flying in that thin atmosphere. It'll fall like a brick, as our flying tech is designed for earth atmosphere, not martian.
<br />

<br />
I think it'd be wise to take a communications sattelite along and deploy it in Martian orbit, since it'll make communicating with the rovers a hell of a lot easier. They could also take along another rover or two, but eventually the mass starts to add up so that may not be practical. Once there they can do their discovery stuff and have a good time.
<br />

<br />
They'll use the solid-state fuel to lift off from Mars, and the ion drives again to return home. You'd probably want to dump the solid state boosters after Mars lift-off, it would reduce the ship's mass, enough to make the ion drives more efficient getting them home. Minus the weight of most of their equipment, the return trip is going to go a hell of a lot faster than the trip out.
<br />

<br />
There's a lot of risk in this. I think getting them to Mars will be easy. Getting them landed safely, and with the ability to lift off again, is going to be incredibly difficult. If anything goes wrong chances are they won't be able to fix it on their own and return.
<br />

<br />
You're looking at numbers for this thing that close in on the trillion dollar mark for a return trip. A tenth that for the one way version. The question becomes what we can afford, not what we want. I'd love to see them do it right and bring them back, though. That would be awesome.
<br />

<br />
Perhaps our idiotic government should try cooperating with other space agencies and making it a joint effort. It's the best way I can think of to defray the cost of going the whole way. Of course, that means they'd have to share the tech and the discoveries, and that's something we simply don't do, because we're morons.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
